Task.elementDescription: a piece of work to be done

Route.elementDescription: a path with a defined start and finish

Aktion.elementDescription: an action performed by a Klimber

Absorb.elementDescription: to reduce the effect of a physical force

Modify.elementDescription: to change something slightly, especially to make it more correct, effective

Ama.elementDescription: to support something physically, often by leaning it against something else

Crawl.elementDescription: to move along on hands and knees or with your body stretched out along a surface

Drag.elementDescription: to move something by pulling it along a surface

Drop.elementDescription: to fall or to allow something to fall

Eval.elementDescription: the process of judging or calculating the quality, importance, amount, or value of something

Fall.elementDescription: to suddenly go down onto the ground or towards the ground without intending to or by accident

Hinge.elementDescription: Hinging at the hips means bending forward from the hip joint while maintaining a neutral spine

Hook.elementDescription: something curved or bent like a hook used for catching, holding, or pulling

Insert.elementDescription: to put something inside something else

Knot.elementDescription: a join made by tying together the ends of a piece or pieces of rope

Lift.elementDescription: to move something from a lower to a higher position

Kryos.elementDescription: to freeze the Degrees of Freedom of a particular joint

Onda.elementDescription: a movement back and forth or in a curve from a fixed point

Orbit.elementDescription: to move or cause something to move in a circular or curving path around a central point or line

Pop.elementDescription: the rapid contraction and release of muscles, producing rhythmic and precise movements

Push.elementDescription: to move something into a different position, usually one that is further away from you

Preserve.elementDescription: to keep something as it is, especially in order to prevent it from decaying or being damaged or destroyed

Reach.elementDescription: to stretch out your arm or leg to get or touch something

Rip.elementDescription: to pull apart; to tear or be torn

Slot.elementDescription: to put something into a narrow hole or opening

Stack.elementDescription: things arranged one on top of another

Tangent.elementDescription: A tangent is also a line that touches a curve or solid at a particular point

Swap.elementDescription: exchanging one Kontakt for another Kontakt, usually exchanging to another limb, but you can swap within limbs such as from [Kontakt|Knee] to [Kontakt|Foot]

Toggle.elementDescription: a linkage system (bars connected by pivots) that converts small input motion into large output force or creates a strong locking action, often using an over-center principle where resistance peaks at the center, snapping the mechanism into a locked end position, ideal for clamps, presses, and switches. It works by amplifying force as links align, making them very strong when locked but requiring significant force to move them through the locked-straight position

Transport.elementDescription: to bring a tool from one place to another without using it

Roll.elementDescription: rolling motion, a combination of rotation and translation, like a wheel moving without slipping

Wrap.elementDescription: to put a body part around something

Difficulty.elementDescription: the state or quality of being hard to do, understand, or deal with, encompassing problems, obstacles, lack of ease, or a challenging nature, often measured as a level of complexity requiring significant effort or skill to overcome

Competition.elementDescription: a situation in which someone is trying to win something or be more successful than someone else

Strategy.elementDescription: a detailed plan for achieving success in situations

Tactic.elementDescription: a specific action intended to get a particular result

Tool.elementDescription: an object that helps you to do a particular activity

FallProtection.elementDescription: an object or device which prevents a klimber from becoming injured from the impact of a fall

Rope.elementDescription: a strong, thick cord of strands (such as natural or synthetic fibers, or wire) that are twisted or braided together into a larger and stronger form

Karabiner.elementDescription: an object used for attaching two things, for example by a Klimber for attaching a rope to a harness. It is oval or like a letter D in shape, with a part that opens and closes

Helmet.elementDescription: a strong, hard hat that covers and protects the head

Sling.elementDescription: a tied or sewn loop of webbing or cord

Glove.elementDescription: a piece of clothing that is worn on the hand and wrist for warmth or protection, with separate parts for each finger

Clothing.elementDescription: things you wear to cover your body

Kit.elementDescription: a bag used to transport tools

Effectiveness.elementDescription: successful or achieving the results that you want

Efficiency.elementDescription: the quality of achieving the largest amount of useful work using as little energy, fuel, effort, etc. as possible

Error.elementDescription: something performed that is not correct, not accurate, or does not give the right result

Anatomy.elementDescription: the scientific study of the body and how its parts are arranged

Body.elementDescription: the whole physical structure that forms a person or animal

Spine.elementDescription: the line of bones down the centre of the back that provides support for the body and protects the spinal cord

Ribs.elementDescription: a set of bones that curve around from your back to your chest

Head.elementDescription: the part of the body above the neck where the eyes, nose, mouth, ears, and brain are

Cranium.elementDescription: the hard bone case that gives an animal's or a human's head its shape and protects the brain

Ear.elementDescription: either of the two organs, one on each side of the head, by which people or animals hear sounds, or the piece of skin and tissue outside the head connected to this organ

Face.elementDescription: the front of the head, where the eyes, nose, and mouth are

Neck.elementDescription: the part of the body that joins the head to the shoulders

Arm.elementDescription: either of the two long parts of the upper body that are attached to the shoulders and have the hands at the end

Scapula.elementDescription: a large, flat bone on each side of your back below your shoulder that helps to increase the range of movement of your arm

Humerus.elementDescription: the long bone in the upper half of your arm, between your shoulder and your elbow

Forearm.elementDescription: the lower part of the arm, between the wrist and the elbow

Hand.elementDescription: the part of the body at the end of the arm that is used for holding, moving, touching, and feeling things

Thumb.elementDescription: the short, thick finger on the side of your hand that makes it possible to hold and pick things up easily

IndexFinger.elementDescription: the finger next to the thumb

MiddleFinger.elementDescription: the longest finger on the hand

RingFinger.elementDescription: the longest finger on the hand

PinkyFinger.elementDescription: the smallest finger on each hand

Leg.elementDescription: one of the parts of the body of a human or animal that is used for standing or walking

Hips.elementDescription: the area below the waist and above the legs at either side of the body, or the joint that connects the leg to the upper part of the body

Femur.elementDescription: the long bone in the upper part of the leg

Tibia.elementDescription: the large bone at the front of the lower leg

Foot.elementDescription: the part of the body at the bottom of the leg on which a person or animal stands

Physiology.elementDescription: the scientific study of the way in which the bodies of animals work

Endurance.elementDescription: used to describe sports or activities that demand the ability to make a lot of physical effort over a long period of time

Suppleness.elementDescription: the quality of being able to bend easily or be bent easily

Strength.elementDescription: the degree to which something is strong or powerful

InjuryPrevention.elementDescription: physical harm or damage to someone's body caused by an accident

Nutrition.elementDescription: the substances that you take into your body as food and the way that they influence your health and athletic performance

Gym.elementDescription: an indoor facility with artificial walls featuring textured panels and plasts, designed for rock climbing, bouldering, and training in a safe, controlled environment

Sediment.elementDescription: solid material, such as dirt or minerals, that falls to the bottom of a liquid

Material.elementDescription: solid material, such as dirt or minerals, that falls to the bottom of a liquid

Natural.elementDescription: as found in nature and not involving anything made or done by people

Litosfera.elementDescription: the solid outer layer of a planet

Hydrosfera.elementDescription: all of the water, ice, and water vapor at or near the surface of a planet

Water.elementDescription: a clear liquid, without color or taste, that falls from the sky as rain

Snow.elementDescription: the small, soft, white pieces of ice that sometimes fall from the sky when it is cold, or the white layer on the ground and other surfaces that it forms

Plant.elementDescription: a living thing that grows in earth, in water, or on other plants, usually has a stem, leaves, roots, and flowers, and produces seeds

Bush.elementDescription: a plant with many small branches growing either directly from the ground or from a hard stem, giving the plant a rounded shape

Poales.elementDescription: a low, green plant that grows naturally over a lot of the earth's surface, having groups of very thin leaves that grow close together in large numbers

Moss.elementDescription: a very small, green or yellow plant that grows especially in wet earth or on rocks, walls, and tree trunks

Dendron.elementDescription: a tall plant that has a wooden trunk and branches that grow from its upper part

Rock.elementDescription: the dry solid part of the earth's surface, or any large piece of this that sticks up out of the ground

Granite.elementDescription: is a coarse-grained, intrusive igneous rock composed primarily of quartz and feldspars.

Limestone.elementDescription: a sedimentary rock consisting predominantly of calcium carbonate, primarily in the form of the mineral calcite or aragonite. It is defined geologically as a rock containing at least 50% calcium carbonate.

Sandstone.elementDescription: a clastic sedimentary rock composed primarily of sand-sized mineral or rock grains (specifically, particles between 0.0625 mm and 2 mm in diameter) that have been naturally cemented together

Basalt.elementDescription: a dark-colored, fine-grained, extrusive igneous rock that forms from the rapid cooling of magnesium-rich and iron-rich (mafic) lava at or very near a planet's surface. It is the most common volcanic rock type on Earth, making up most of the oceanic crust

Atmosfera.elementDescription: a mixture of gases that surrounds Earth

AirTemperature.elementDescription: a measure of how hot or cold the atmosfera is, which is determined by the average thermal energy of air molecules

Humidity.elementDescription: containing extremely small drops of water in the air

Smoke.elementDescription: the grey, black, or white mixture of gas and very small pieces of carbon that is produced when something burns

Animal.elementDescription: anything that lives and moves, including people, birds, etc.

Bird.elementDescription: a creature with feathers and wings, usually able to fly

Mosquito.elementDescription: a creature with feathers and wings, usually able to fly

Fungi.elementDescription: any of various types of organisms that get their food from decaying material or other living things

Wind.elementDescription: a current of air moving approximately horizontally, especially one strong enough to be felt

Klimon.elementDescription: the outer or top part or layer of something

Texture.elementDescription: the quality of something that can be decided by touch

Abduction.elementDescription: the movement of a part of the body away from the central part of the body or from another body part

Adduction.elementDescription: the movement of a body part toward the midline of the body or the midline of a limb. This motion primarily occurs within the coronal (frontal) plane.

Extension.elementDescription: a movement that increases the angle between two bones at a joint, or the act of straightening a limb

Flexion.elementDescription: a movement that decreases the angle between two bones at a joint, or the act of bending a limb

PerimeterLine.elementDescription: the outer edge of an area of land or the border around it

StraightLine.elementDescription: moving or placed in a position that continues in one direction without bending or curving

Position.elementDescription: an object's location relative to a reference point (origin) using coordinates, distances, and directions

CircuitPassage.elementDescription: a path which start and finishes in the same position

BoustroPassage.elementDescription: is a style of writing in which alternate lines of writing are reversed, with letters also written in reverse, mirror-style

CircumventPassage.elementDescription: to avoid something by going around it

Geometry.elementDescription: the area of mathematics relating to the study of space and the relationships between points, lines, curves, and surfaces

Density.elementDescription: the number of people or things in a place in relation to the size of the place

Direction.elementDescription: the position towards which someone or something moves
elementBetanyms: while the rear half rotates in the opposite direction

AbsoluteDirection.elementDescription: one of the four main points of the compass: north, south, east, and west

RelativeDirection.elementDescription: describes location or orientation based on your own body or a nearby object, using terms like left, right, forward, backward, up, and down, as opposed to fixed compass points (north, south) which are absolute directions

Displacement.elementDescription: the change in an object's position

Distance.elementDescription: the total length of the actual path traveled by an object during its motion, irrespective of the direction of travel

Div.elementDescription: the div element serves as a versatile container for other KlimBeta elements. It doesn't inherently convey any semantic meaning about its content

Line.elementDescription: a long, thin mark on the surface of something

Morfos.elementDescription: the structure and form of animals and plants

Orientation.elementDescription: the position of something in relation to its surroundings

Point.elementDescription: a fundamental, zero-dimensional object representing a precise location in space, having no size, length, or width, only position

MidPoint.elementDescription: a fundamental, zero-dimensional object representing a precise location in space, having no size, length, or width, only position

Shape.elementDescription: outline of an object. Shapes are closed by an outline or boundary, which is made up of points, lines and curves

Logic.elementDescription: the rigorous study of valid reasoning and inference, using abstract symbols and precise rules to analyze the structure of arguments, independent of content, to determine if conclusions necessarily follow from premises. It provides the foundation for mathematical proofs, ensuring that steps taken in reasoning are deductively sound, essentially formalizing thought processes into mechanical systems.

Probability.elementDescription: the level of possibility of something happening or being true

Affordance.elementDescription: a use or purpose that a thing can have, that people notice as part of the way they see or experience it
elementBetanyms: ability to function as a whole rather than isolated segments
allows for a greater range of

Site.elementDescription: a surface which affords a Kontakt

Passage.elementDescription: the specific continuous sequence of positions in space (or spacetime) that an object or system occupies as it moves from an initial state to a final state

Constraint.elementDescription: something that controls what you do by keeping you within particular limits
elementBetanyms: degrees of freedom in relation to

Fortuna.elementDescription: chance and the way it affects your life

Frequency.elementDescription: the number of instances something happens within a particular period
elementBetanyms: often at the root of some

PropositionalLogic.elementDescription: a formal system that studies how to combine simple declarative statements (propositions, which are either true or false) using logical connectives (like AND, OR, NOT, IF...THEN) to form complex statements, analyzing the truth and validity of these compound statements and the logical relationships between them, without delving into the internal structure of the propositions themselves. It provides a framework for constructing valid arguments and understanding truth conditions in mathematics, philosophy, and computer science

ConditionalLogic.elementDescription: a fundamental concept used to control the flow of a program based on whether certain conditions are met. It allows for decision-making within algorithms by executing different blocks of code depending on the evaluation of a Boolean expression (which is either true or false)

Consequence.elementDescription: the result or effect of an action, decision, or event. It refers to something that follows logically from a preceding occurrence.

ZigzagLine.elementDescription: a line or pattern that looks like a Z or a row of Zs joined together

elementBetanyms: primary rotation on the horizontal axis

ElasticEnergy.elementDescription: the energy stored in an object when it's temporarily deformed (stretched, compressed, or twisted) by an external force, allowing it to return to its original shape and release that energy

PotentialEnergy.elementDescription: stored energy an object has due to its position, configuration, or state

NormalForce.elementDescription: the support force a surface exerts on an object touching it, acting perpendicular (at a 90 angle) to the surface to prevent the object from passing through

ProjectileMotion.elementDescription: the movement of an object under the influence of gravity alone, following a curved path called a trajectory

Ritmo.elementDescription: a regularly repeated pattern of sounds or beats used in music, poems, and dances

Syncopation.elementDescription: a type of musical rhythm in which strong notes are not on the beat

Tempo.elementDescription: the speed at which an event happens

Dynamics.elementDescription: the branch of physics that studies how forces affect the motion of objects

Force.elementDescription: an interaction that causes a mass to accelerate, which means it can change an object's velocity or shape

CentripetalForce.elementDescription: a net force that acts on an object moving in a curved or circular path, directed toward the center of curvature or axis of rotation. This center-seeking force is necessary to constantly change the object's direction and keep it from flying off in a straight line due to inertia, as described by Newton's first law of motion

FrictionForce.elementDescription: a contact force that opposes the relative motion, or attempted motion, between two systems in contact. It acts tangentially, or parallel, to the contact surface between the objects

GravityForce.elementDescription: the force that pulls objects toward each other

Pressure.elementDescription: the force applied perpendicular (normal) to a surface per unit area over which that force is distributed

TensionForce.elementDescription: the pulling force that is transmitted axially through a string, rope, cable, or similar one-dimensional continuous object when it is pulled tight by forces acting from opposite ends

Energy.elementDescription: the quantitative property of a system that enables it to do work or cause change

Inertia.elementDescription: the fundamental property of an object that describes its resistance to changes in its state of motion (whether at rest or moving with constant velocity). This concept is formally defined by Sir Isaac Newton's first law of motion.

Momentum.elementDescription: the quantity of motion of a moving body, measured as a product of its mass and velocity

Power.elementDescription: the rate at which work is done or energy is transferred, meaning how quickly energy changes form or moves from one place to another, expressed as work (W) or energy (E) per unit of time (t). Its standard SI unit is the Watt (W)

Work.elementDescription: the energy transferred to or from an object when a force causes it to move over a distance

Torque.elementDescription: the measure of the force that causes an object to rotate or turn around an axis

KineticEnergy.elementDescription: is the energy an object possesses due to its motion

Kinematics.elementDescription: description of motion (how objects move) without considering the forces, mass, or energy involved that cause the motion. It is often referred to as the geometry of motion

Speed.elementDescription: the rate at which someone or something is able to move or operate

Velocity.elementDescription: the speed of something in a given direction

Acceleration.elementDescription: the rate of change of the velocity of an object with respect to time

Jerk.elementDescription: the rate of change of an object's acceleration with respect to time. It is the third derivative of position (or displacement) and the first derivative of acceleration

Time.elementDescription: the irreversible, continuous progression of existence and events from the past, through the present, into the future, enabling the measurement of duration, intervals, and rates of change, often conceptualized as the fourth dimension intertwined with space in spacetime. It's the fundamental framework for sequencing reality, measured by clocks and calendars, and described by physics as a dimension inseparable from the three spatial dimensions

Commitment.elementDescription: a promise or firm decision to do something

TimeEstimation.elementDescription: the process of predicting the time needed to complete a specific task

LongTermMemory.elementDescription: he cognitive process for storing and retrieving information over extended periods, from minutes to decades

ShortTermMemory.elementDescription: the brain's temporary workspace for holding a small amount of information (around 4-7 items) for a brief period, typically 15-30 seconds

ViaMemory.elementDescription: our brain's ability to learn, store, and recall information about locations, paths, and the arrangement of objects in space, crucial for navigation, orientation, and forming cognitive maps

WorkingMemory.elementDescription: your brain's temporary mental workspace, allowing you to hold and manipulate a small amount of information (like numbers, words, or steps) for immediate use while performing complex tasks like reasoning, learning, comprehension, and problem-solving. It's like a mental scratchpad

Compassion.elementDescription: a strong feeling of empathy and sadness for other people's suffering or bad luck and a desire to help

MindState.elementDescription: your temporary mental and emotional conditionyour mood, attitude, or cognitive condition at a specific time

Mindset.elementDescription: a person's way of thinking and their opinions

Control.elementDescription: the ability or power to decide or strongly influence the particular way in which something will happen or someone will behave

GoodEase.elementDescription: a good mood itself can increase cognitive ease

Music.elementDescription: a pattern of sounds made by musical instruments, voices, or computers, or a combination of these, intended to give pleasure to people listening to it

Playlist.elementDescription: a list of pieces of music chosen by someone to listen to

PressureSense.elementDescription: the sensory ability to perceive sustained distortion or indentation of the skin and deep tissues

Attention.elementDescription: the process of selectively concentrating on specific information from the environment or internal thoughts while intentionally ignoring other, irrelevant stimuli

Cognition.elementDescription: all forms of knowing and awareness, such as perceiving, conceiving, remembering, reasoning, judging, imagining, and problem solving

CognitiveEase.elementDescription: the mental state of effortless information processing, where familiar, clear, and simple information feels true, good, and safe, leading to confidence and reduced mental strain

Clarity.elementDescription: the mental state in which thoughts are organized, focused, and free from confusion or brain fog. It is the ability to perceive, understand, and organize information effectively, enabling clear decision-making, problem-solving, and purposeful action

Priming.elementDescription: a phenomenon in which exposure to one stimulus influences how a person responds to a subsequent, related stimulus

Repetition.elementDescription: something that happens in the same way as something that happened before

FeelsGood.elementDescription: very satisfactory, enjoyable, pleasant, or interesting

FeelsFamiliar.elementDescription: the state of being well-acquainted or having good knowledge/mastery of someone or something

FeelsEffortless.elementDescription: seeming not to need any effort

FeelsTrue.elementDescription: being what exists, rather than what was thought, intended, or stated

Decision.elementDescription: a choice that you make about something after thinking about several possibilities

Estimation.elementDescription: the process of finding an estimate or approximation, which is a value that is usable for some purpose even if input data may be incomplete, uncertain, or unstable

Identification.elementDescription: recognizing or proving what something is by categorizing it (term, class, distinguishing features)

Judgement.elementDescription: a decision that you make, or an opinion that you have, after considering all the facts in a situation

Emotion.elementDescription: physiological and psychological responses that help people react to events or situations.

Anger.elementDescription: a strong feeling that makes you want to hurt someone or be unpleasant because of something unfair or unkind that has happened

Disgust.elementDescription: a strong feeling of disapproval and dislike at a situation, object or person

Fear.elementDescription: a primal, protective emotion triggered by a perceived immediate threat, prompting a biochemical & physiological alarm (like increased heart rate, adrenaline) to prepare the body for fight or flight, keeping us safe from harm. Unlike anxiety, which is future-oriented and vague, fear is a direct response to a present, identifiable danger, involving brain centers like the amygdala, and serves as a vital survival mechanism, though it can become problematic if excessive

Joy.elementDescription: a profound, intense positive emotion, deeper than fleeting happiness, often stemming from meaningful connections, alignment with values, purpose, or unexpected positive events, and it signifies deep well-being, boosting resilience, motivation, and connection, with types including passive contentment and active engagement. Unlike happiness (a broader life evaluation), joy is a transcendent state that can emerge even amid hardship, characterized by a sense of blessedness, exhilaration, or deep delight

Sadness.elementDescription: an emotion resulting from the loss of someone or something important

Memory.elementDescription: the ability to remember information, experiences, and people

Arousal.elementDescription: a state of mental alertness, attention, or energy. It involves the cognitive processes that activate the brain's alertness and attentiveness. This state is distinct from physical or emotional arousal, though they are often related

Confidence.elementDescription: a feeling of trust or belief in a person, thing, or one's own abilities. It is a state of mind marked by an absence of uncertainty, shyness, or embarrassment.

Mindfulness.elementDescription: Mindfulness means paying attention in a particular way: on purpose, in the present moment, and non judgmentally

FlowState.elementDescription: A state in which people are so involved in an activity that nothing else seems to matter; the experience is so enjoyable that people will continue to do it even at great cost, for the sheer sake of doing it

Senses.elementDescription: a biological system for sensation, detecting stimuli (light, sound, chemicals) via specialized cells in sense organs, converting them into neural signals the brain interprets, encompassing traditional ones like sight/hearing but also more complex ones (balance, body position)

Audio.elementDescription: the physiological process and ability to perceive sounds by detecting vibrations (sound waves) as periodic changes in the pressure of a surrounding medium, such as air or water.

Touch.elementDescription: the complex sensory system responsible for the body's ability to perceive physical stimuli through specialized receptors primarily located in the skin, as well as in muscles, joints, and internal organs

Compression.elementDescription: is the conscious appreciation of sustained mechanical deformation or indentation of the skin and underlying deep tissues

Proprioception.elementDescription: the sense of self-movement, force, and body position

Sight.elementDescription: the physical sense or faculty by which light stimuli received by the eye are interpreted by the brain and constructed into a representation of objects in space
